"Rating: 95 out of 100"
"Appearance is a cloudy orange tone with a short white head, kind of like part of some sunsets. Its` nose has cherry, sour apples and yeast present. There is tartness there, no question about it. It tastes of oak, spice, more of those fruits, and more of that tart aspect to it. Mouthfeel is at a medium level, fair carbonation level. An interesting sour from The Bruery and a pretty damn good one."
"I’m going to throw this out there, and I don’t say this lightly: Sour in the Rye is my favorite Bruery beer. The balance of spicy rye malt, tart bacteria and oak is just perfect. Like I said, I finished the whole bottle myself, and I’d do it again in a heartbeat. Glorious stuff."
"Overall: Very tasty. Very drinkable. The sour beer and the spice from the rye play well together. Very well balanced."
"Bottle from Hopscotch. Pucker up and get ready for a wild ride. This beer is full of awesome sourness. First I didn’t taste or smell any rye, but I didn’t care. From nose to mouth, I would say it was like sour tasting pop rocks in your mouth. The higher abv really helped give this beer some extra body but without the booze taste. This is a Top 3 American made sour and I would love to have another bottle."
"Decent enough, though a bit of an underperformer. A little more contrast would work wonders."
"O: Great stuff and finally a good use of a newly overused grain!"
"Very interesting, the texture is something completely else; luckily I knew what to expect from the rye, but it certainly threw my wife for a loop (she really likes light bodied lambics, and so this beer definitely doesn’t really appeal to here). I am definitely enjoying this beer, if for nothing else than its unique texture then so be it. There isn’t really a whole lot of complexity here; I would have expected that the rye would have added more wild graininess and spiciness to this brew and even the funkiness is focused on the lactic acidity rather than more wild notes from Brettanomyces or other wild-bugs that can produce a lot of “off” flavors. If there were a lot of sour, heavily laden rye beers out there this wouldn’t be much of a standout, but as it is there is not, so this is enjoyable for its relative uniqueness if nothing else; it is indeed an experience."
"I guess the majority of BA must really like drinking salad dressing. Or it's the rarity. Hard to tell."
"Ultimately, this beer is just overdone like nobody's business. Drinking a whole bottle is nigh on impossible, I'm going to have to make a salad dressing or something with this. I would not age this any longer as at this point, my bottle is already a lot more sourer than an of the C&C La Folie's I've had. This seems like a recent development as some of the early reviews mention balance, low sourness, neither of which are evident from this sample."
"Pours a orangish brown. A touch of white head. Looks fairly pretty. Smells spicy and tart. Not particularly sour on the nose or tongue. There is a spicy and sour burn that is really interesting. Tons of rye on. The tongue that combines nicely with nose. Fairly thick pn the tongue, not a lot of carbonation. Overall interesting but not something i would seek out"
"D: I'm not a huge fan of sours but this is one of the better ones I've had. Nice balance with the sourness and the rye malt."
"O - Good sour, but I really hope that the Bruery crew can figure out a way to cut back on the acetic qualities in their sours. These are all A beers but for the vinegar notes/taste. Maybe its the OC water?"
"Aroma is loaded with fruit, pears are dominant, as much as you would say blueberries are in blabaer, this has the most pronounced pear aroma and flavor I have ever come across. Light tartness builds as it comes up to room temperature giving you that horse funk you are looking for but keeping it light with tons of light grain and bready notes back building the pear and now light sour apple. Each sip seems to get even more complex then the one before. Rich pear and apple flavors, light sour notes, hints of grass and liht bready malts, complex as hell. Perfect carbonation, light, bubbly, full enough to coat the tonue, perfectly done with the abv so well hidden I thought it was 8 percent."
"Shared this one with the group at the ""Evening Wood"" tasting graciously hosted by cmrillo! Served from bottle into a Mikkeller flute. Poured a hazy red-orange with a very minimal off-white head. There was no lacing throughout the glass. The aroma was comprised of sweet malt, sour, tart, and acetic acid. The flavor was of sweet malt, sour, tart, funk, and vinegar. It had a light feel on the palate with medium-high carbonation. Overall this brew was just plain excellent. It was also a REALLY big hit with the other who were tasting it as well. The look of this brew isn't that nice, but it definitely made up for this fact with the flavor and aroma without a doubt. Really wish I could have gotten multiple bottles of this from the Reserve Society this year, but I am glad I got to share this one with quite a few good BAs and others who appreciated it. Definitely worth your time to try or trade for."
"I knew I needed to try this beer as soon as I heard about it, I love the bruery and Catcher In the Rye. Pretty murky beer, very dark amber brown with a reddish hugh. Not such great head retention, just not the best looking beer. Strong aroma of dry oak and vinegar, very vinous. A very nice aroma with some grape skins and hints of sweet rye. Rye, yup its there in the flavor, but plenty more oak and vinous notes. A bit sharp and biting, with a great lactic sour character. My only critique is that this beer could have more depth and complexity. Dry, period. Just a great beer. I love Bruery sours and this does not disappoint, plus the bottle is awesome."
